[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 214. This includes 19 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 61 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 countries from the South East Asia region, 22 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 54 countries (including 19 territories) from the Americas region, and 48 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
------------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 35 681 new cases (42.8% of the global newly reported cases), and 3734 deaths (57.1%) were recorded for this 24-hour period. Of the newly confirmed cases in the region, 62.4% were reported by the USA, followed by Brazil at 19.4%, and Peru at 10.7%. Recognizing the USA data are overshadowing the regional proportions, without including the reported newly confirmed cases from the USA, Brazil reported 51.7% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Peru at 28.5%, Mexico at 8.4%, and Chile at 7.7%. Ecuador did not report any new cases.

The European region reported 32 209 new cases (38.6% of the global newly reported cases) and 2458 deaths (37.6%). Russia reported 34.9% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, the UK 19.3%, France 13.0%, Turkey 7.0%, Italy 4.5%, and Spain 3.1%.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 7968 new cases (9.6% of the global newly reported cases) and 175 deaths (2.7%). Saudi Arabia reported 21.2% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Iran at 21.1%, Pakistan at 19.3%, Qatar 10.4%, and the United Arab Emirates at 6.9%.

The African region reported 1497 new cases (1.8% of the global newly reported cases) and 23 deaths (0.4%). South Africa reported 24.7% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Guinea-Bissau at 14.4%, Nigeria at 13.0%, Algeria at 10.6%, Senegal at 7.0%, and the DR Congo at 6.2%.

The Western Pacific region reported 1300 new cases (1.6% of the global newly reported cases) and 34 deaths (0.5%). Singapore reported 60.6% of the newly reported cases, followed by the Philippines at 24.6%, and Japan at 8.4%. Removing Singapore from the denominator has the Philippines at 62.5%, Japan at 21.3%, Malaysia at 8.8%, and Australia at 5.1%.

The South East Asia region reported 4810 new cases (5.8% of the global newly reported cases) and 115 deaths (1.8%). India reported 74.0% of newly reported cases, followed by Bangladesh at 16.4% and Indonesia at 7.6%. Removing India from the denominator, Bangladesh represents 63.3% of the newly reported cases, Indonesia represents 29.4%, the Maldives at 3.6%, and Sri Lanka at 2.1%.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 7 May 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. One sees the contribution of the ongoing epidemics in Europe and the increasing cases in the Americas region, fueled by the USA, but other countries are following suit. The curve tends to drop over the weekends and rebounds following the weekend. Europe has not been rebounding as high at the end of the weekend, demonstrating decreasing newly confirmed cases. South East Asia has been gradually increasing as the cases continue increasing in India.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: It is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Johns Hopkin's CSSE or Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have, at times, significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the John Hopkins CSSE or Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.MPP]
